{"id":"2108.11568","submitter":"John Maclean","authors":"John Maclean, J. E. Bunder, I. G. Kevrekidis, A. J. Roberts","title":"Adaptively detect and accurately resolve macro-scale shocks in an\n  efficient Equation-Free multiscale simulation","comments":"35 A5 pages, 12 figures, submitted to SISC","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS cs.NA math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Equation-Free approach to efficient multiscale numerical computation\nmarries trusted micro-scale simulations to a framework for numerical\nmacro-scale reduction -- the patch dynamics scheme. A recent novel patch scheme\nempowered the Equation-Free approach to simulate systems containing shocks on\nthe macro-scale. However, the scheme did not predict the formation of shocks\naccurately, and it could not simulate moving shocks. This article resolves both\nissues, as a first step in one spatial dimension, by embedding the\nEquation-Free, shock-resolving patch scheme within a classic framework for\nadaptive moving meshes. Our canonical micro-scale problems exhibit\nheterogeneous nonlinear advection and heterogeneous diffusion. We demonstrate\nmany remarkable benefits from the moving patch scheme, including efficient and\naccurate macro-scale prediction despite the unknown macro-scale closure.\nEquation-free methods are here extended to simulate moving, forming and merging\nshocks without a priori knowledge of the existence or closure of the shocks.\nWhereas adaptive moving mesh equations are typically stiff, typically requiring\nsmall time-steps on the macro-scale, the moving macro-scale mesh of patches is\ntypically not stiff given the context of the micro-scale time-steps required\nfor the sub-patch dynamics.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 26 Aug 2021 03:44:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-27"}
